# Quantium Virtual Internship – Retail Analytics (Task 1)

## Objective
Analyse customer purchasing behaviour in the chips category to identify key customer segments and provide strategic recommendations for category growth.

---

## Key Insights

- Mainstream Young Singles/Couples drive the highest total sales  
- Budget Older Families drive high volume through bulk purchases  
- Price differences across segments are minimal → behaviour is the key driver  
- Smaller packs are preferred by singles, larger packs by families  

---

## Data Preparation

### Load Data

```python
import pandas as pd

transactions = pd.read_excel('QVI_transaction_data.xlsx')
customers = pd.read_csv('QVI_purchase_behaviour.csv')
Data Cleaning
# Convert date
transactions['DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(transactions['DATE'], origin='1899-12-30', unit='D')

# Remove non-chip products
transactions = transactions[~transactions['PROD_NAME'].str.lower().str.contains('salsa')]

# Remove outlier customer
outlier_customer = transactions[transactions['PROD_QTY'] == 200]['LYLTY_CARD_NBR'].unique()
transactions = transactions[~transactions['LYLTY_CARD_NBR'].isin(outlier_customer)]

Findings:

Salsa products removed to focus only on chips
Outlier customer removed (non-typical retail behaviour)
Dataset cleaned for accurate analysis
Exploratory Analysis
Transactions Over Time
transactions_per_day = transactions.groupby('DATE').size().reset_index(name='COUNT')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
plt.plot(transactions_per_day['DATE'], transactions_per_day['COUNT'])
plt.title('Transactions Over Time')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

📊 Figure: Transactions Over Time


Findings:

Sales peak in December (holiday season)
Drop on Christmas Day (store closure)
Feature Engineering
Pack Size
transactions['PACK_SIZE'] = transactions['PROD_NAME'].str.extract('(\d+)').astype(float)
import seaborn as sns

sns.histplot(transactions['PACK_SIZE'], bins=20)
plt.title('Pack Size Distribution')
plt.show()

📊 Figure: Pack Size Distribution


Findings:

Most common sizes: 150g–175g
Larger packs indicate family consumption behaviour
Brand Extraction
transactions['BRAND'] = transactions['PROD_NAME'].str.split().str[0]

transactions['BRAND'] = transactions['BRAND'].replace({
    'RED': 'RRD'
})
Merge Data
data = pd.merge(transactions, customers, on='LYLTY_CARD_NBR', how='left')

Findings:

No missing values after merge
Customer segmentation successfully integrated
Customer Segment Analysis
Total Sales by Segment
import seaborn as sns

sales_segment = data.groupby(['LIFESTAGE', 'PREMIUM_CUSTOMER'])['TOT_SALES'].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(data=sales_segment, x='LIFESTAGE', y='TOT_SALES', hue='PREMIUM_CUSTOMER')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

📊 Figure: Total Sales by Segment


Findings:

Highest sales from:
Mainstream Young Singles/Couples
Budget Older Families
Mainstream Retirees
Customers by Segment
customers_segment = data.groupby(['LIFESTAGE', 'PREMIUM_CUSTOMER'])['LYLTY_CARD_NBR'].nunique().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(data=customers_segment, x='LIFESTAGE', y='LYLTY_CARD_NBR', hue='PREMIUM_CUSTOMER')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

📊 Figure: Customers by Segment


Findings:

Mainstream Young Singles/Couples = largest segment
Sales partially driven by population size
Average Units per Customer
units = data.groupby(['LIFESTAGE', 'PREMIUM_CUSTOMER']).agg({
    'PROD_QTY': 'sum',
    'LYLTY_CARD_NBR': 'nunique'
}).reset_index()

units['AVG_UNITS_PER_CUSTOMER'] = units['PROD_QTY'] / units['LYLTY_CARD_NBR']

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(data=units, x='LIFESTAGE', y='AVG_UNITS_PER_CUSTOMER', hue='PREMIUM_CUSTOMER')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

📊 Figure: Avg Units per Customer


Findings:

Families purchase the highest volume
Indicates bulk buying behaviour
Average Price per Unit
data['PRICE_PER_UNIT'] = data['TOT_SALES'] / data['PROD_QTY']

price_segment = data.groupby(['LIFESTAGE', 'PREMIUM_CUSTOMER'])['PRICE_PER_UNIT'].mean().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(data=price_segment, x='LIFESTAGE', y='PRICE_PER_UNIT', hue='PREMIUM_CUSTOMER')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

📊 Figure: Avg Price per Unit


Findings:

Price differences are minimal
Purchasing behaviour is the main driver of sales
Deep Dive: Target Segment
Mainstream Young Singles/Couples
target = data[
    (data['LIFESTAGE'] == 'YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES') &
    (data['PREMIUM_CUSTOMER'] == 'Mainstream')
]
Brand Affinity
